Now I can see the C implementation of `verify_console_object`:

```c
void verify_console_object()
{
	Assert(Player_num > -1);
	Assert(Players[Player_num].objnum > -1);
	ConsoleObject = &Objects[Players[Player_num].objnum];
	Assert(ConsoleObject->type == OBJ_PLAYER);
	Assert(ConsoleObject->id == Player_num);
}
```

This function:
1. Asserts Player_num > -1
2. Asserts Players[Player_num].objnum > -1


3. Sets ConsoleObject to point to the player's object
4. Asserts the object type is OBJ_PLAYER
5. Asserts the object id equals Player_num

The key side effect is setting `ConsoleObject = &Objects[Players[Player_num].objnum]`. For porting this, I need to fetch Player_num, Players[Player_num].objnum, and the object's type and id fields, then write back the ConsoleObject pointer assignment.

Let me check the D1 version too.

